  "text": "Across these three repositories, gRPC error status propagation follows a consistent pattern with some implementation variations:\n\n## etcd-io/etcd\n\nIn etcd, error status codes are defined centrally in `api/v3rpc/rpctypes/error.go`. This file creates pre-defined gRPC Status errors using `status.Error(codes.*)` with specific codes like `codes.InvalidArgument`, `codes.NotFound`, `codes.FailedPrecondition`, `codes.Unavailable`, `codes.ResourceExhausted`, `codes.OutOfRange`, `codes.Canceled`, `codes.DeadlineExceeded`, `codes.PermissionDenied`, `codes.DataLoss`, and `codes.Unauthenticated`. Examples include `ErrGRPCEmptyKey` (InvalidArgument), `ErrGRPCKeyNotFound` (InvalidArgument), and `ErrGRPCInvalidAuthToken` (Unauthenticated).\n\nError propagation happens in `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/util.go` through the `togRPCError()` function, which uses a `toGRPCErrorMap` to map internal domain errors to pre-defined gRPC status codes. This centralized mapping approach (lines 35-96) ensures consistency across the RPC layer. The gRPC gateway translation occurs in generated files like `api/etcdserverpb/gw/rpc.pb.gw.go`, where `status.Errorf(codes.InvalidArgument, ...)` calls are used to generate HTTP responses through the standard gRPC gateway mechanism.\n\n## kubernetes/kubernetes\n\nIn Kubernetes, gRPC error creation is more distributed. Files like `staging/src/k8s.io/kubelet/pkg/cri/streaming/errors.go` directly create gRPC Status errors with specific codes (line 29: `grpcstatus.Error(codes.ResourceExhausted, ...)`). The file also defines `WriteError()` function (lines 33-51) that explicitly translates CRI streaming gRPC status codes to HTTP response status codes using a switch statement on `s.Code()`, converting `codes.NotFound` to HTTP 404 and `codes.ResourceExhausted` to HTTP 429 (TooManyRequests).\n\nFor gateway-based translation, Kubernetes uses vendored `grpc-ecosystem/grpc-gateway/v2/runtime` libraries. The `vendor/github.com/grpc-ecosystem/grpc-gateway/v2/runtime/errors.go` file contains the core `HTTPStatusFromCode()` function (lines 34-38) that converts gRPC codes to HTTP status codes. This function is used in `runtime/handler.go` (line 232) to set HTTP response headers automatically.\n\n## grafana/grafana\n\nGrafana creates gRPC errors directly in various interceptors and service files. In `pkg/services/grpcserver/interceptors/auth.go`, the authenticator creates errors like `status.Error(codes.Unauthenticated, ...)` (line 71, 79, 104, 114, 118, 123) and `status.Error(codes.PermissionDenied, ...)` (line 118, 123) for authentication and authorization failures.\n\nError translation to HTTP status happens in `pkg/storage/unified/resource/errors.go`. The `AsErrorResult()` function (lines 122-165) uses `runtime.HTTPStatusFromCode(st.Code())` from grpc-gateway to convert extracted gRPC status codes to HTTP status codes. It also provides helper functions like `NewBadRequestError()` and `NewNotFoundError()` that create errors with specific HTTP status codes.\n\nFor the OpenFGA integration in `pkg/services/authz/zanzana/server/openfga_server.go`, Grafana uses custom error handlers (lines 225-234) with `runtime.WithErrorHandler()` that leverages OpenFGA's `serverErrors.ConvertToEncodedErrorCode()` to map gRPC status codes to custom error codes before sending HTTP responses.\n\n## Cross-Repository Patterns\n\nAll three repositories use `google.golang.org/grpc/status` for creating and handling gRPC Status errors. The key difference in approaches is:\n\n1. **etcd** uses centralized error definition and mapping through `toGRPCErrorMap`\n2. **Kubernetes** uses direct error creation with explicit gRPC-to-HTTP conversion in specific handlers plus grpc-gateway's automatic conversion\n3. **Grafana** uses distributed error creation with flexible conversion through grpc-gateway's `HTTPStatusFromCode()` and custom error handler plugins\n\nThe error code families used across all three repositories include: InvalidArgument, NotFound, FailedPrecondition, Unavailable, ResourceExhausted, OutOfRange, Canceled, DeadlineExceeded, PermissionDenied, Unauthenticated, DataLoss, and Unknown."
}

